text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild]]%0a%0a!ASL and Medicine%0a%0a:Author: VikramM%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aDiscrimination in the way deaf or hearing impaired people have access to the medical community%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0ahttps://www.apa.org/pi/disability/resources/publications/newsletter/2013/11/deaf-community%0ahttps://www.bu.edu/sph/news/articles/2018/healthcare-language-barriers-affect-deaf-people-too/%0a%0aThe two articles listed describe the inequity in healthcare knowledge and access that deaf or hard of hearing people can experience while using ASL. The core of the several ways ASL users may be discriminated against in terms of healthcare and medicine is the gap in communication.%0a%0aThis gap can be present in the form of a lack of materials and education about health. With less knowledge about the healthcare system and about their own health, people may not a doctor as often and may know less about their own health and body. These circumstances can lead to more severe health problems that could have been prevented. %0a%0aThe other side of the gap in communication is that not all doctors or other health professionals are fluent in ASL and interpreters/translators are not always readily available to help. This can lead to significantly worse outcomes for patients and can overall make seeking medical care a much more daunting task. This in turn can again make people that use ASL less likely to receive appropriate levels of medical care.%0a %0aThe article from the American Psychological Association includes that varying degrees of hearing loss are becoming more prevalent, so the issues present for those hard of hearing may become critical for a larger share of the population if the use of ASL rises. %0a%0a%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210508-035916-762930#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!ASL acquisition %0a-> - meng_s%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aApart from the lack of healthcare professionals fluent in ASL and/or ASL translators, another barrier to ASL acquisition is the stance that deafness is a condition to be treated. In this article, it was mentioned that the mission of the Alexander Graham Bell Association for the Deaf and Hard of Hearing (AGB) is to “[help] families, health care providers and education professionals understand childhood hearing loss and the importance of early diagnosis and intervention”. Such a stance perpetuates the idea that a Deaf child cannot lead a fulfilling life and assumes that Deaf people are desperate to be part of the hearing world. However, we can tell from the protests against the Listening and Spoken Language Symposium organized by AGB led by Deaf people mentioned in the article that this is far from the truth. ASL is important to many in the Deaf community and oralist methods, such as cochlear implants, oral speech and lip reading, treats ASL as inferior to spoken languages. It is important to promote ASL acquisition among deaf children rather than impose oralist methods on them.%0ahttps://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2013/08/understanding-deafness-not-everyone-wants-to-be-fixed/278527/%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210508-035916-762930#%0a#foxbegin 210508-035918-362310#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!ASL acquisition %0a-> - meng_s%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aApart from the lack of healthcare professionals fluent in ASL and/or ASL translators, another barrier to ASL acquisition is the stance that deafness is a condition to be treated. In this article, it was mentioned that the mission of the Alexander Graham Bell Association for the Deaf and Hard of Hearing (AGB) is to “[help] families, health care providers and education professionals understand childhood hearing loss and the importance of early diagnosis and intervention”. Such a stance perpetuates the idea that a Deaf child cannot lead a fulfilling life and assumes that Deaf people are desperate to be part of the hearing world. However, we can tell from the protests against the Listening and Spoken Language Symposium organized by AGB led by Deaf people mentioned in the article that this is far from the truth. ASL is important to many in the Deaf community and oralist methods, such as cochlear implants, oral speech and lip reading, treats ASL as inferior to spoken languages. It is important to promote ASL acquisition among deaf children rather than impose oralist methods on them.%0ahttps://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2013/08/understanding-deafness-not-everyone-wants-to-be-fixed/278527/%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210508-035918-362310#%0a#foxbegin 210508-035951-123510#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!ASL acquisition %0a-> - meng_s%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aApart from the lack of healthcare professionals fluent in ASL and/or ASL translators, another barrier to ASL acquisition is the stance that deafness is a condition to be treated. In this article, it was mentioned that the mission of the Alexander Graham Bell Association for the Deaf and Hard of Hearing (AGB) is to “[help] families, health care providers and education professionals understand childhood hearing loss and the importance of early diagnosis and intervention”. Such a stance perpetuates the idea that a Deaf child cannot lead a fulfilling life and assumes that Deaf people are desperate to be part of the hearing world. However, we can tell from the protests against the Listening and Spoken Language Symposium organized by AGB led by Deaf people mentioned in the article that this is far from the truth. ASL is important to many in the Deaf community and oralist methods, such as cochlear implants, oral speech and lip reading, treats ASL as inferior to spoken languages. It is important to promote ASL acquisition among deaf children rather than impose oralist methods on them.%0ahttps://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2013/08/understanding-deafness-not-everyone-wants-to-be-fixed/278527/%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210508-035951-123510#%0a#foxbegin 210508-040013-670820#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!ASL acquisition %0a-> - meng_s%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aApart from the lack of healthcare professionals fluent in ASL and/or ASL translators, another barrier to ASL acquisition is the stance that deafness is a condition to be treated. In this article, it was mentioned that the mission of the Alexander Graham Bell Association for the Deaf and Hard of Hearing (AGB) is to “[help] families, health care providers and education professionals understand childhood hearing loss and the importance of early diagnosis and intervention”. Such a stance perpetuates the idea that a Deaf child cannot lead a fulfilling life and assumes that Deaf people are desperate to be part of the hearing world. However, we can tell from the protests against the Listening and Spoken Language Symposium organized by AGB led by Deaf people mentioned in the article that this is far from the truth. ASL is important to many in the Deaf community and oralist methods, such as cochlear implants, oral speech and lip reading, treats ASL as inferior to spoken languages. It is important to promote ASL acquisition among deaf children rather than impose oralist methods on them.%0ahttps://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2013/08/understanding-deafness-not-everyone-wants-to-be-fixed/278527/%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210508-040013-670820#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a#foxbegin 210513-194856-173400#%0a(:div1 class=messagehead:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-13.05.2021 - 12:48-] &nbsp; %0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c%0a{[foxdelrange button 210513-194856-173400 {$FullName} ]}%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1end:)%0a!!!!!saumyaB%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0a'''Interpreters'''%0a>>messageitem%3c%3c%0aI wonder if healthcare interpreters are able to convey the exact feelings and pain of the patients effectively. Since the information is going through another person, could part of the message get obscured if the interpreter isn't listening too closely? This could have detrimental results :( %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210513-194856-173400#%0a#foxbegin 210501-063654-315920#%0a(:div1 class=messagehead:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c   %0a[-30.04.2021 - 23:36-] &nbsp; %0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1 authgroup @tas:)%0a>>rfloat%3c%3c%0a{[foxdelrange button 210501-063654-315920 {$FullName} ]}%0a>>%3c%3c%0a(:if1end:)%0a!!!!!Abi_S%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0a'''health equity '''%0a>>messageitem%3c%3c%0athis also leads to health equity issues, patient may also not fully understand what doctor is saying to them %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210501-063654-315920#%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: A:)%0a(:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild:)
